<br>
I wasn't aware that summoned items stayed in banks after logging.  This little bit was removed 2 years ago.  Now, leaving a corpse full of rods is possible...would be kinda creepy dragging a corpse around and looting it bag by bag as the raid progresses.../shiver<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The way to &quot;fix&quot; T-Rods is to make them even more efficient like 250m for 250hps per click. Just make them no drop and mage only. Tune some of the higher lvl encounters down and problem is solved. I would not stress one second if I never could hand another class a vial of my mana.&quot; - Wezloc<br>
<br>
I don't know what crack you're smoking.  Tune down high level encounters...its just that simple?  VI would end up breaking 75% of them in the process.<br>
<br>
I don't mind making rods.  It gives me a purpose on a raid.  It kinda feels good to finish an uber encounter where I was the only mage present and knowing that I was an integral part of making that kill possible, not just fluff DPS.<br>
<br>
As for the wrong classes eating your rods, I'd say that's a guild discipline issue and some enforcing needs to be made.  Clerics and spot heal druids are the only ones who can touch the rods.  Others sit on the ground.  Shamans got reamed everytime they touched a rod, now they don't.  Wizards get extras when clerics have had their fill.  <br>
<br>
<br>
I would love non-lore mod rods, especially on CR.  Make as many as I can while waiting for res, then dump them on the ground when I zone in.  I don't know about you, but I don't have the inventory space to clean out the bank or whatever just to haul around rods to chain click at will.  Non-lore would at least keep me from wasting mana when I make a rod, forgetting I have one buried in a bag already (much like the epic, *man* that pisses me off, and I have to wait out the refresh...sorry, another thread)<br>
<br>
Non-lore rods would take the aggravation out of trying to motivate everyone to hold a rod until called to drop it near the clerics before charging an uber.<br>
<br>
